STEMDIFF :: Convert 4D-STEM data to powder diffractogram¶

  • Sample:
    • Au nanoislands
    • Local backup: D:\DATA.SH\STEMDIFF\X_TESTING\1AU
  • Input: 4D-STEM datafiles (= a 2D array of 2D diffractograms from a pixelated STEM detector)
  • Output: a 2D-powder diffraction pattern (usually 3 types/versions of the pattern: sum_all, sum_f, sum_fd)

1. Initialize¶

Import modules¶

In [1]:
# STEMDIFF
# (basic package, which converts 4D-STEM data to 2D-diffractogram
import stemdiff.detectors, stemdiff.gvars
import stemdiff.io, stemdiff.dbase, stemdiff.psf, stemdiff.sum
In [2]:
# PLOTTING
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

stemdiff.io.set_plot_parameters(); plt.show()

Define basic I/O data¶

  • SDATA = source data = experimental data parameters: detector type, location of the datafiles.
  • DIFFIMAGES = Diffraction images = diffractogram characteristics estimated from inspection of diffractograms.
In [4]:
# (1) Define source data
SDATA = stemdiff.gvars.SourceData(
    detector  = stemdiff.detectors.TimePix(),
    data_dir  = r'./DATA',
    filenames = r'*.dat')
In [5]:
# (2) Set parameters of diffraction images
DIFFIMAGES = stemdiff.gvars.DiffImages(
    imgsize=150, psfsize=155,
    ctype=2, csquare=30, cintensity=0.8,
    peak_height=100, peak_dist=9)
In [6]:
# (3) Output directory for STEMDIFF calculations
SDIR = r'./SDIFF/'

2. Database of all files¶

  • We will calculate a database of all datafiles, which will contain (for each datafile):
    • DatafileName = the filename of the datafile (relative to DATAFILES.data_dir)
    • Xcenter,Ycenter = the intensity center of the datafile = primary beam position
    • MaxInt = the maximum detected intensity of the datafile
    • Peaks = the number of detected peaks in the datafile
    • S = Shannon entropy of the datafile/image
  • Technical notes:
    • The calculation may take a few minutes, but it has to be performed just once.
    • You can skip/comment the command if the database has already calculated and saved.
    • Xcenter,Ycenter are determined for UPSCALED datafiles for the sake of accuracy - see below.
In [7]:
# (1) Calculate database
# (Comment if database already calculated 
df1 = stemdiff.dbase.calc_database(SDATA, DIFFIMAGES)
In [8]:
# (2) Save database
# (Comment if database already calculated
stemdiff.dbase.save_database(df1, output_file=SDIR+'dbase_all.zip')

MaxInt - homogeneity of background¶

  • Maxint = maximum intensity detected on an image/array.
  • Maxint values should be neither too high (overflows) nor too low (high absorption).
  • Optimal datasets from given detector have Maxint in the interval (max.det.intensity/2; max.det.intensity).
In [15]:
# Print detector name and maximum detector intensity
# (maximum detector intensity = maximal value the detector can measure
print('Detector name     :', SDATA.detector.detector_name)
print('Maximum intensity :', SDATA.detector.max_intensity)

Detector name     : TimePix
Maximum intensity : 11810
In [16]:
# Plot maximum intensity for each datafile
plot = df1.plot.line(y=['MaxInt'], color='green')
plot.set_xlabel('Datafiles')
plot.set_ylabel('Primary beam intensity')
plot.grid()

Xcenter,Ycenter - stability of primary beam position¶

  • Xcenter,Ycenter should be close to center and should not vary much.
  • The center has been determined (and saved in database) for upscaled image for better accuracy.
  • Note: an optimal upscaling coefficient is hardcoded for given detector; available in SDATA.detector.upscale
In [17]:
# Print basic detector data, namely expected position of the center.
# (the detector values are hardcoded in stemdiff.io.detectors
# (the detector in given experiment is defined in section 1, variable SDATA
print('Detector/image size   :', SDATA.detector.detector_size)
print('Upscaling coefficient :', SDATA.detector.upscale)
print('Upscaled image size   :',
      SDATA.detector.detector_size * SDATA.detector.upscale)
print('Upscaled image center :',
      SDATA.detector.detector_size * SDATA.detector.upscale // 2)

Detector/image size   : 256
Upscaling coefficient : 4
Upscaled image size   : 1024
Upscaled image center : 512

plot.grid()

Correlation between no-of-peaks and entropy¶

  • Strong Peaks--S correlation indicates reasonable, good dataset.
  • Peaks = number of peaks is estimated for each diffractogram (and saved in database df1).
  • S = Shannon entropy is calculated for each diffractogram (and saved in the database of all files = df1).
In [19]:
plot = df1.plot.scatter(x='Peaks', y='S', color='red', marker='x')
plot.set_xlabel('Number of peaks')
plot.set_ylabel('Shannon entropy')
plot.grid()

  • We will create a sub-database (df2) containing these datafiles.
  • Summation using only files with strong diffractions usually yields better results.

4.2. Files for PSF calculation¶

  • We will create a sub-database (df3) of the datafiles showing just primary beam.
  • PSF can be estimated from these files (if they contain just primary beam + a few weak diffractions).

4.3. Calculate PSF¶

  • The estimation of 2D-PSF function from datafiles with weak diffractions (df3.
  • Note: If this does not give good results, we will have to use other methods of PSF estimation.
In [29]:
# Calculate PSF from files in df3
psf = stemdiff.psf.PSFtype1.get_psf(SDATA, DIFFIMAGES, df3)
In [30]:
# Save the calculated PSF (in NumPy format)
stemdiff.psf.save_psf_to_disk(psf, SDIR+'psf.npy')
In [31]:
# Show the calculated PSF
stemdiff.psf.plot_psf(psf, plt_type='3D', plt_size=30)

6. STEMDIFF final result¶

  • STEMDIFF converts a 4D-STEM dataset to a single 2D-powder diffraction pattern.
  • Three methods/outputs: (i) sum all files, (ii) sum filtered, (iii) sum filtered + deconvoluted.
  • The final 2D-diffractograms are shown below and saved in output directory (as defined in SDIR variable).

2D diffraction patterns¶

In [41]:
stemdiff.io.set_plot_parameters(size=(24,8))
In [42]:
# Plot the final 2D-diffractograms
stemdiff.io.plot_2d_diffractograms(
    data_to_plot = [
        [SDIR+'sum_all_16bit.png', 'All files'],
        [SDIR+'sum_f_16bit.png',   'Filtered files'],
        [SDIR+'sum_fd_16bit.png',  'Filtered + deconvoluted files']],
    icut=150, cmap = 'viridis',
    output_file=SDIR+'sums_final.png', dpi = 300)
